Car Data ML Project

date: 2023-06-12

Introduction to Sports Car Data Analysis

Sports cars hold a significant place in modern culture, epitomizing speed, aesthetic appeal, and often serving as symbols of status and power. The diversity within the category of sports cars is vast, encompassing a range of designs from the visually stunning to the less aesthetically pleasing, varying speeds from the lightning-fast to the relatively sluggish, and different origins including European, Japanese, and American models. Given the variety found in the sports car segment, it presents an ideal subject for in-depth analysis through statistical methods.

What is the Purpose of this analysis?

The objective of this project is to develop a predictive model that can ascertain the price of a sports car based on key attributes such as its speed, model year, and engine specifications. By inputting specific values into our model, we aim to estimate the market price of any given vehicle, including hypothetical models conceived for analytical purposes. This capability not only enhances our understanding of the factors influencing car valuations but also provides a versatile tool for forecasting the potential market value of future car designs.

Exploring and Organizing the Data

What does this dataset have to offer?

dim(sportscar_data)
## [1] 1007    8

The dataset under examination comprises 1,007 observations, each representing a distinct vehicle, and includes eight variables. For the purposes of this analysis, the variable of interest, or response variable, is the cars price. We will employ four predictor variables to forecast this price: engine size, horsepower, torque, and acceleration (0-60 mph time).

Engine Size: This variable represents the total volume of all the cylinders within the engine, typically measured in liters. In the context of this project, engine size is a crucial predictor as it often correlates with the vehicles power output and, by extension, its market value.

Horsepower: This is a measure of the engines power output. One horsepower equates to the power required to lift 550 pounds one foot off the ground in one second. In automotive contexts, higher horsepower is generally associated with higher performance levels, influencing the vehicles price.

Torque: Measured in foot-pounds (ft-lbs), torque reflects the rotational force the engine generates. Vehicles with higher torque can typically accelerate more forcefully from a standstill, impacting their desirability and price.

Acceleration (0-60 mph time): This measure indicates how quickly a vehicle can accelerate from a standstill to 60 miles per hour. Its a critical performance indicator, with faster acceleration times often commanding higher prices in the sports car market.

Based on prior knowledge of automotive performance, it is hypothesized that there is a significant correlation among torque, 0-60 mph acceleration time, horsepower, and engine size. These interrelationships are anticipated due to the intrinsic mechanical and performance-related dependencies linking these variables.

Creating Models

Now we must create our models. To do this, were going to split our data up, create our model recipes, and cross validate.

Splitting Data

The fundamental goal of developing our models is to accurately predict outcomes for new data inputs. To achieve this, we must divide our data into training and testing subsets. The training set trains the models, while the testing set evaluates their performance on unseen data, with the ideal model demonstrating minimal error on the testing set. While a common practice is to use a 70/30 split between training and testing data, we have opted for a 65/35 split. This adjustment allows us to ensure a more thorough representation of data in the testing phase, which is viable given the substantial size of our dataset. Additionally, we will stratify the data by the 0-60 time to maintain a balanced representation of fast and slow cars in both sets.

Recipe Creation

This recipe based on our data will serve to create all of our models. For our predictors, we will use 0-60 time (in seconds), horsepower (in hp), torque (in lb-ft), and engine size (in liters) to predict car price.

sportscar_recipe = recipe(Price ~ EngineSize + Horsepower + Torque + ZeroToSixty , data= sportscar_data) %>% 
    step_center(all_predictors()) %>% 
    step_scale(all_predictors()) 
  



#sportscar_recipe = recipe(Price..in.USD ~ Horsepower + Torque..lb..ft)

K fold Cross Validation

sportscar_folds = vfold_cv(sportscar_train, v = 10, strata = ZeroToSixty)

K-fold cross-validation is a technique used to assess the performance of a model by estimating its accuracy on unseen data. It addresses the issue of overfitting and provides a more reliable estimate of the models generalization ability.

In k-fold cross-validation, the dataset is divided into k ( in our case 10) approximately equal-sized folds. One fold is held out as the testing set, and the remaining k-1 (9)f olds are used as the training set. The model is trained on the training set and then evaluated on the testing set. This process is repeated k times, each time using a different fold as the testing set and the remaining folds as the training set.

By repeating the process k times and averaging the results, we obtain a more accurate estimate of the models performance. It helps in reducing the bias and variance associated with evaluating a model on a single train-test split. A good way to think of it is this; imagine the model trains on one fold, and then is tested by the next one, and then that fold serves to also train the data. As we move through the folds, the accuracy of our models will be higher than if we only used one training set.

Making our Models


To build our models efficiently, we have pre-saved the results due to their long run times. We selected Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) as our evaluation metric, which measures the average difference between the models predictions and the actual values. A lower RMSE indicates better performance, as it means the predicted values are closer to the actual values. Normalizing the data is crucial for accurate RMSE calculation.

Fitting our Models

# LINEAR REGRESSION 
lm_model = linear_reg() %>% 
  set_engine("lm")


# POLYNOMIAL REGRESSION
# Adjusting the recipe because the tuning parameter must be added in the recipe for polynomial regression
# Tuning the degree
poly_rec = sportscar_recipe %>% 
  step_poly(EngineSize, Horsepower , Torque , ZeroToSixty , degree = tune())

poly_spec = linear_reg() %>% 
  set_mode("regression") %>% 
  set_engine("lm")

# K NEAREST NEIGHBORS
# Tuning the number of neighbors
knn_model <- nearest_neighbor(neighbors = tune()) %>% 
  set_mode("regression") %>% 
  set_engine("kknn")

# ELASTIC NET
# Tuning penalty and mixture
elastic_spec <- linear_reg(penalty = tune(), 
                           mixture = tune()) %>% 
  set_mode("regression") %>% 
  set_engine("glmnet")

In the initial phase of our model development, weve selected four predictive models, each with unique attributes:

Elastic Net Regression: This method blends ridge and lasso regressions features, addressing multicollinearity and overfitting through regularization, making it robust for correlated data.

Linear Regression: Fundamental and widely used, this model identifies a linear relationship between dependent and independent variables, providing straightforward interpretations of variable impacts.

Polynomial Regression: Enhancing linear regression, this model fits a non-linear relationship through polynomial terms, effectively capturing curvilinear trends in the data.

K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN): Adaptable for regression, KNN predicts a points value by averaging the values of the K nearest neighbors, offering a flexible non-parametric approach.

These methodologies will be fine-tuned and evaluated to predict car prices accurately within our dataset.

# LINEAR REGRESSION 
lm_workflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(lm_model) %>% 
  add_recipe(sportscar_recipe)



# POLYNOMIAL REGRESSION
poly_wf <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(poly_spec) %>% 
  add_recipe(poly_rec)

# K NEAREST NEIGHBORS
knn_workflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(knn_model) %>% 
  add_recipe(sportscar_recipe)

# ELASTIC NET
elastic_workflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(sportscar_recipe) %>% 
  add_model(elastic_spec)

We then set up our workflows.

# POLYNOMIAL REGRESSION
degree_grid <- grid_regular(degree(range = c(1,5)), levels = 5)

# K NEAREST NEIGHBORS
knn_grid <- grid_regular(neighbors(range = c(1,15)), levels = 5)

# ELASTIC NET
elastic_grid <- grid_regular(penalty(range = c(-5, 5)), mixture(range = c(0,1)), levels = 10)





set.seed(190)

Using Our Model

Now, we can use our model to predict the price of a vehicle from 2021-2022 based on its performance metrics. Lets go through some use cases.

First, lets say that I am a recently hired corporate employee with some extra cash laying around, and Im looking to purchase an entry level sports car. I value horsepower over torque slightly, and although I want a sports car, I want it to be fuel efficient, not over the top with speed, and somewhat affordable. Based on my knowledge of automobiles, I would place this car at 3.5 liters, 350 horsepower, 280 lb-ft of torque, and a zero to sixty time of 4.7. Lets see how much this car would cost, according to our model.

Conclusion

After cleaning our data, analyzing the variables and how they interact with each other, building out model, training our model, testing our model, and running final diagnostics, weve finally built something that accurately predicts a cars price based on given values for horsepower, torque, 0 to 60 time, and engine size.

The model that worked best for us was a K nearest neighbors model. KNN predicts a new cars price based on the K closest data points in the feature space. (in our case, K=1). KNN works because similar cars have similar prices. The model that performed the poorest was the Elastic Net model. This is because Elastic Net is a linear model, and linear models struggle with multicollinearity, which our parameters have lots of.

Now we have a model that can accurately predict the price of a vehicle made in 2021-2022. As seen above in the Using Our Model section, we can feed our model any number within the valid ranges for Horsepower, Torque, 0-60 time, and Engine size, and get a corresponding price.

Limitations and Further Research

As a car enthusiast, I created this project in order to quantify the tedious and enigmatic world of car pricing. Ultimately, I fell short of this goal for two main reasons.

Model Focus

The original aim of this study was to predict specific car models using performance metrics and price as predictors. However, this goal was not achieved due to the complexities associated with a categorical response involving over 1000 distinct car models. The challenges were mainly due to the high dimensionality and sparse distribution of data across numerous categories, which hindered effective learning and prediction accuracy in the model. This necessitated a reevaluation of the analytical approach.

Lack of Significant Parameters in Dataset

While Price, Horsepower, 0-60 Time, and Engine Size are critical metrics, they represent only a fraction of the factors relevant in the car purchasing decision process. A more comprehensive dataset would ideally encompass additional parameters such as fuel efficiency, depreciation rates, availability or rarity, 60-130 time and cylinder count. Including these variables could significantly enhance the quantitative analysis of the multifaceted issue involved in selecting a car, providing a more holistic view of each vehicles attributes and their implications for buyers.

Year

An additional crucial variable that was overlooked in the initial analysis is a comprehensive Year parameter. Although the dataset included year data, a closer examination revealed a predominance of vehicles from the years 2021 and 2022. This uniformity in model years enabled the analysis of car prices without the need for inflation adjustments. However, it also restricted our ability to investigate temporal variations in car prices and to explore how the age of a vehicle influences the purchasing decision. This limitation highlights the importance of a diverse temporal range in the dataset to fully understand pricing dynamics and consumer preferences over time.

Moving forward

As mentioned earlier, many faults of this project were due to the data that was available. Car pricing data is hard to come by, as most of it is proprietary. However, I have seen independents conduct amazing high level analysis on car markets, so I know that the data is out there. My ongoing goal is to publish a program that can make the car buying process easier for everyone from the casual buyer to the enthusiast.
